ions have on our nation's public school system, coupled with the glacier-like speed at which any change whatsoever is even considered there, is it any wonder that families with a choice make sure that their children are placed in private schools? Perhaps the author should pick up a copy of Thomas Sowell's 1993 classic: Inside American Education, and read it cover to cover. It's message was pretty grim back then. It's just as compelling now. In it, he says: &quot;We must face up to what educators have actually done, as distinguished from what they have said: They have taken our money, betrayed our trust, failed our children, and then lied about the failures with inflated grades and pretty words.....&quot; Ms Benedikt writes from  a plateau of pure ignorance. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1055" language="en" documentId="2691" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Iscarius" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:28PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2691" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1055"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>